BONANZA CREEK LTER

Juvenile Snowshoe Hares

Jake Nyiri

Introduction

This exploratory analysis examines some of the data collected at multiple Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest Long-Term Ecological Research sites in Alaska from 1998-2010. This is a large-scale ecological and climate research center located in boreal forest and tundra around the city of Fairbanks. Relationships between sex and weight of juvenile snowshoe hares in the area are examined, as well as any potential relationship between weight and limb length.

Data and Methods

Counts and measurements of juvenile snowshoes hares were collected from trapping regimes at three sites in the LTER over 12 years (Kielland, K., F.S. Chapin, R.W. Ruess, and Bonanza Creek LTER. 2017. Snowshoe hare physical data in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest: 1999-Present ver 22. Environmental Data Initiative.). The locations consisted of a riparian near-stream area, lowlands dominated by balck spruce, and mature, upland boreal forest with a mix of alder, birch, and spruce. Hare weight, sex, foot length, and ear length were recorded. In this analysis, weights were compared across the three sites and summary statistics prepared for both sexes of hare. A two-sample t-test was used to explore differences between the average weights of male and female hares, with a Cohens d effect size determined. Relationships between hare weight and hind foot length were examined and a linear model created to try to describe the relationship. All analysis was conducted with R 3.6.2


Hare Counts
We first explored general trends in the observed population over the temporal range of the data by visualizing the number of hares trapped each year.


Figure 1
Juvenile Snowshoe Hare Counts (1998-2010) The counts are absolute irrespective of sex or trapping location.

The counts appear to decrease over the timespan of the study, from a maximum of 126 to a minimum of 2. However, for two years (2002 and 2009) there were no identifiable juveniles counted, and the majority of the ages are listed as NA. If we treat those years as 0 juveniles counted then the average yearly count is 27 with a median of 15.5. If we do not include those years at all, the average count is 31.5 with a median of 18.5. The large number of NA ages in these years indicates that a more regimented sampling and identification system amy be in order.


Hare Weights Across Sample Locations
Next we analyzed the weights of the captured hares across both sex and grid location in the sample area.


Figure 2
Juvenile Snowshoe Hare Weights By Sex and Location. The colored dots represent individual hare measurements. The boxes show the limits of the middle 50% of each dataset, and the line and diamond in each box represent the median and mean, respectively.

The data indicates that average female weights are similar in the upland and riparian areas (808g and 824g respectively) and somewhat higher in the lowland (1022g). The average male weight varied less by location (1073g for lowland, 950g for upland and 929g for riparian), however the range of male weights was much wider in the riparian area than the lowlands. For both sexes the largest number of captures occurred in the riparian area, and the least in the lowlands.


Comparison Of Juvenile Hare Weights By Sex
Captured hares were grouped by sex and analyzed for any significant difference in their average weights utilizing a two-sample t-test.

Table 1: Hare Weights By Sex
Sex Mean Weight(g) Standard Deviation Number Trapped
Female 855.4 292.3 197
Male 945.9 333.2 163

After checking for normality of the data using a QQ plot, we do not see a result for either sex which is as normalized as we would prefer, especially at the low end of the weights, but we still consider the data sample sufficiently normal to apply a two-sample t-test. Male hares had a mean weight of 945.9g \(\pm\) 333.2g and females had a mean weight of 855.4g \(\pm\) 292.3g. The difference in the means of the two samples was 90.5g, or a 10.05% difference, and although this was found to be significant (Welchs t-test, t(325.02) = -2.71, p = 0.007, the effect size was not very large (Cohens d = -0.29).


Juvenile Hare Foot Length and Weight Modeling
Finally we created a simple linear model to try to explore any potential relationship between hare weight and length of their rear feet.


Figure 3
Juvenile hare hind foot length as a function of weight. Each dot represents an individual hare, with males and females grouped together. The red line represents the regression line, with the regression equation displayed in the lower right.

After regression, the use of a linear model appears to be questionable. The weight of a hare is not a very good predictor of rear leg length (p < 0.001, R2 = 0.2547), with a slope of the model of 0.028 mm*g-1, indicating a slight increase in foot length with each gram of weight increase. The two datasets are not very correlated (Pearsons r of 0.505). An examination of graphs of the residuals for the model reveal several potential conflicts with the assumptions of a linear model, including non-normality of the data the further away from the mean of the dataset modeled, and non-equal variance of the residuals around the fitted line. Indeed, a cursory look at the regression line on the graph indicates a linear model does not fit this data well.


CONCLUSION
1. Sampling method inconsistency may be leading to uncounted juveniles and unidentifiable sex or age of hares.
2. The number of juveniles being recorded appears to be decreasing sharply over time even when accounting for potential sampling inaccuracies.
3. While there is a difference in the recorded mean weight of juvenile hares based on sex, the significance may not be high enough to report a trend. Further sampling may help to resolve this.
4. A direct relationship between weight and foot length with no other influences seems tenuous at best. Accounting for differences in sex and area lived in may further elucidate this relationship.
